l multi-bit assignments use concatenation correctly (e.g., `{q[30], q[31]}`).\\n2.  When handling the right shift, ensure the source bit $q[i+1]$ is handled carefully, especially for $q\'[31]$ (which should come from $q[32]$, assumed 0).\\n3.  The tap logic must be implemented using an `if/else` structure within the combinational calculation for the next state, or by explicitly setting the next state based on the tap condition.\\n\\n*Self-Correction on Shift:* A right shift means $q\'[i] = q[i+1]$. The MSB $q\'[31]$ gets the input/feedback. If we are shifting right, $q\'[31]$ must receive the feedback signal. If the taps define the feedback, and we XOR with $q[0]$, this is complex. Given the phrasing, we stick to the derived rule: $q\'[i] = (q[i+1] \\text{ XOR } (\\text{TapMask}[i] \\text{ AND } q[0]))$. \\n\\nLet $T_{mask}$ be a 32-bit vector where $T_{mask}[i]=1$ if $i \\text{ is a tap index } \\text{\\textbraceleft} 31, 22, 2, 1 \\text{\\textbraceright$. \\n$q\'[i] = q[i+1] \\text{ XOR } (T_{mask}[i] \\text{ AND } q[0])$.\\nWe must define $q[32]=0$.\\n\\nThis leads to the final structure.\\n",\n    "module": "module TopModule (\\n    input  logic clk,\\n    input  logic reset,\\n    output logic [31:0] q\\n);\\n\\n    // Internal register for the LFSR state\\n    logic [31:0] q_reg;\\n\\n    // Tap definitions based on specification (32->31, 22, 2, 1)\\n    // Taps are at indices 31, 22, 2, 1.\\n    localparam TAPS_MASK = 32\'b1 << 31 | 32\'b1 << 22 | 32\'b1 << 2 | 32\'b1 << 1;\\n\\n    // Initialize q_reg to a known state (e.g., 0) before reset takes effect.\\n    initial begin\\n        q_reg = 32\'h0;\\n    end\\n\\n    // Sequential logic for LFSR update\\n    always @(posedge clk)\\n    begin\\n        if (reset)\\n        begin\\n            // Synchronous reset to 32\'h1\\n            q_reg <= 32\'hFFFFFFFF;\\n        end\\n        else\\n        begin\\n            logic [31:0] q_next;\\n            \\n            // Determine the next state based on the 