h $q[i-1]$ (or $q[0]$ as the feedback source).\\n    *   Standard Galois LFSR shift right: $q\'[i] = q[i+1]$ for all $i$, with $q\'[31]$ determined by the feedback.\\n    *   The description suggests a modification of the right shift: For a tap position $i$, the next value $q\'[i-1]$ is derived differently.\\n    *   Let\'s interpret the specified taps (32, 22, 2, 1) relative to the 32 bits ($q[31]$ to $q[0]$). Since the register shifts right, the new value of $q[i]$ comes from $q[i+1]$. The XOR is with $q[0]$.\\n    *   If $i$ is a tap position, the new value $q\'[i-1]$ is modified.\\n    *   Taps at indices 1, 2, 22 (since 32 is out of bounds for a 32-bit register index).\\n    *   If $i$ is a tap index, the new bit $q\'[i-1]$ (which would normally be $q[i]$) is calculated as $q[i] \\text{ XOR } q[0]$.\\n    *   Taps: {1, 2, 22}.\\n\\n4.  **Shift Logic Implementation (Right Shift):** The general shift is $q\'[i] = q[i+1]$.\\n    *   $q\'[31] = q[32]$ (Not possible, assume $q\'[31] = 0$ or defined by the feedback).\\n    *   $q\'[i] = q[i+1]$ for $i=0$ to 30.\\n    *   $q\'[31]$ is the feedback bit (often $q[0]$ XORed with some tap bits, but here the feedback mechanism is defined by the taps modifying the shift).\\n\\n5.  **Revisiting Galois LFSR Definition:** In a Galois LFSR that shifts right, the new bit $q\'[i]$ is typically $q[i+1]$ unless $i$ is the position corresponding to a tap, where $q\'[i] = q[i+1] \\text{ XOR } q[0]$.\\n    *   Taps at positions 32, 22, 2, 1. These refer to the positions *where* the XOR happens. If we interpret these as the indices $i$ such that $q\'[i] = q[i+1] \\text{ XOR } q[0]$:\\n        *   Tap at 1: $q\'[1] = q[2] \\text{ XOR } q[0]$ (This seems unlikely for a standard LFSR implementation structure).\\n        *   Let\'s use the provided hint structure: \\"a bit position with a \'tap\' is XORed with the LSB output bit (q[0]) to produce its next value, while bit positions without a tap shift right unchanged.\\"\\n        *   This